text.2: Local TV crews are expecting a surge of early-morning viewers after #ElectionNight. TEGNA will have extra reporters to sort through results. https://t.co/OgW1l1JyEH

Meanwhile, USPS trying to deliver lingering ballots as expeditiously as possible https://t.co/Q884zhCzID
text.4: We don't usually see face shields at polling places. During a pandemic, that's just one of the new norms. https://t.co/Hi2D3GBtFu

Campaign reporters agree on how to describe this election cycle, regardless of whether they covered Trump or Biden. 

They told @brianstelter: It's been "surreal." https://t.co/d48KpL028h

text.8: We might not get the final #election results tonight, so in the meantime, it's a good idea to sharpen your media literacy skills so you can be on the lookout for misinformation. Luckily, our MediaWise ambassadors got you covered.
text.10: Audiences have more ways than ever to get their election news: Podcasts and newsletters are getting in on live content. @Mel_Grau writes about The Daily's "experimental" livestream and HEATED's YouTube broadcast. https://t.co/0v5KrR7TEt
text.11: Is the waiting the hardest part? Depends on where you're voting. Some people encountered quarter-mile lines, others zipped in and out (especially for ballot dropoff).
text.12: A hashtag we last saw in 2018 has resurfaced. @HarrisonMantas weighs in. https://t.co/AxYpVKSbZL
text.13: .@AmarisCastillo with an update on worries about markers via WBBM: "Chicago Board of Election officials confirmed Sharpies bleeding through will not impact the choices on the other side."

Tens of thousands of Americans with newly diagnosed cases of coronavirus face a dilemma if they haven't already voted: Are they allowed to vote in person on Tuesday?

Yes—but they need to take precautions to protect poll workers and other voters, CDC says. https://t.co/TAsPUDZvYx
text.18: Journalists, we at @spj_tweets have your backs, today and every day. If you or any journalist you know is arrested or assaulted by law enforcement for doing our jobs, let us know. You’re protected by both the First Amendment and by SPJ. https://t.co/AjhCDCQusB

text.32: Now feels like a good time to thank every editor working behind the scenes, coordinating coverage and editing stories in real time. Grateful for my @AP editors and colleagues who have been working hard ahead of #ElectionDay.
text.33: We've put together a guide to finding good information on #ElectionNight. Follow reliable sources on our curated Twitter list, check poll closing times, and what states might be fast or slow in reporting results. https://t.co/ct81jQwh6m https://t.co/di00FJhO4N
